The architectural foundation of hangar-bridge — Hono HTTP relay, SSE message delivery,
SQLite persistence, MCP stdio peer-agent, channel-tag escape, untrusted-input system
prompt, sender-stamp anti-spoof, roster gate, reply-storm limiter, idempotency keys,
SSE reconnect with cursor resume — was implemented in claude-mesh and is preserved
(or extended) in hangar-bridge per the terms of the MIT License.

hangar-bridge diverges from claude-mesh in the following ways (non-exhaustive):
- Single-tenant per-host shared-secret auth replacing multi-team/admin/human tier
- New envelope kinds `task_dispatch` and `task_result` for cross-host dispatch
- Removal of pair-code distribution flow and admin tier routes
- Bare MCP server registration (--dangerously-load-development-channels server:...)
  rather than plugin-marketplace path
- LAN-first transport (single operator's homelab fleet) without Docker/Caddy

No upstream sync is planned; hangar-bridge treats the inherited code as 100% owned
from 2026-05-17 onward. Upstream was last updated 2026-04-18.
